<F P=100> ISRAEL </F>
<H3> <TI>   Baraq: Troops Moved From Territories to Green Line </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Baraq: Troops Moved From Territories to Green Line </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   TA1404174894 Jerusalem Qol Yisra'el in Hebrew 1605 GMT 14 
Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> TA1404174894 </F>
<F P=104>  Jerusalem Qol Yisra'el </F>
<F P=105>  Hebrew </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Interview with Lieutenant General Ehud Baraq, chief of </F>
staff, by Army affairs correspondent Karmela Menashe; place and 
date not given -- recorded] 
  [Excerpt] [Menashe] Chief of Staff Ehud Baraq, you have 
just returned from a tour of Judaea and Samaria, of Qalqilyah. 
Is the closure being enforced? 
  [Baraq] As far as possible. I met with reserve soldiers 
from a very fine northern Infantry brigade, and I saw that they 
were very well briefed on the need to conduct tighter checks of 
both documents and the license plates on Israeli vehicles 
leaving the territories. In addition, they are properly 
inspecting the trunks of the vehicles and checking under the 
seats. Secondary roads are being cut off, and patrols are 
deploying between the roads and inside the terrain itself. All 
these actions hinder the infiltration of people and warfare 
means into Israel, but we must admit with all honesty that they 
do not eliminate the danger entirely. 
  [Menashe] Has the IDF [Israel Defense Forces] begun 
implementing the order from the prime minister and defense 
minister to move troops from the territories to the 
Israel-territories divide, the Green Line? 
  [Baraq] Yes. Immediately after receiving this order over 24 
hours ago, we started to considerably increase our deployment 
along the divide at the expense of our presence both in Judaea 
and Samaria and in Israel. This is part of some recent changes 
resulting from new emphases in response to the changing 
situation. We are no less responsible for the security of 
Israelis in Judaea and Samaria today than we were yesterday, but 
the recent events -- most notably the events in Hadera and 
'Afula -- revealed that the emphasis of the other side's 
operational activity has shifted to the divide; therefore, it is 
vital that we shift our own activity to that place. [passage 
omitted] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-12988 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drnes073_l_94007" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-NES-94-073 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  14 Apr 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> ISRAEL </F>
<H3> <TI>   Baraq: IDF Operational Troops Not Part of Redeployment </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Baraq: IDF Operational Troops Not Part of Redeployment </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   TA1404200794 Jerusalem Israel Television Channel 1 Network 
in Hebrew 1800 GMT 14 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> TA1404200794 </F>
<F P=104>  Jerusalem Israel Television Channel 1 Network 
in Hebrew 1800 GMT 14 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=105> Hebrew </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Interview with Lieutenant General Ehud Baraq, chief of </F>
staff, by Army affairs correspondent Alon Ben-David; place and 
date not given -- recorded] 
  [Excerpt] [passage omitted] [Ben-David] A week ago we 
witnessed the removal of equipment from IDF [Israel Defense 
Forces] bases in the Gaza Strip. This was done despite the face 
that the negotiations with the PLO are still in progress and no 
agreement on the evacuation of Gaza and Jericho has been signed. 
Has the IDF not evacuated somewhat prematurely? 
  [Baraq] The IDF has brought forward the evacuation date of 
objects and logistics. If necessary, we can remain there just 
as we are for as long as 12 days, 12 months, or 12 years. The 
IDF's operational forces will neither leave nor redeploy in 
accordance with the new plans -- incidentally, the redeployment 
is also inside the Gaza Strip, around the Qatif Bloc, around 
settlements and along traffic axes -- until we achieve an 
agreement we consider reasonable from the security angle and the 
political echelons consider reasonable from the political point 
of view. 
  [Ben-David] We are waging a war against terrorism in the 
north as well. The question is whether our negotiations with 
Syria will be accompanied by protracted terror there, too, 
carried out under Syrian auspices, more or less. 
  [Baraq] In my opinion, we should work on the premise of and 
with a mental and physical preparedness for continuing terror in 
the north. In the long run, however, political arrangements may 
offer a certain chance for a long-term reduction of tension and 
enmity, provided they reflect an appropriate sensitivity to the 
security issue. Nothing can turn us into the Netherlands and 
Belgium or Switzerland and France in this generation, but a 
proper balance of security-related emphases in the political 
content with a technical, a physical military preparedness.... 
[pauses] At present, we face almost no existential threat. 
The State of Israel is very strong today in the sense of being 
able to defend its existence. What is threatened is the 
personal safety of its civilians, who are faced with terror. 
  [Ben-David] We are celebrating our Independence Day, and yet 
the IDF's POW's and MIA's are still not with us. Is there 
anything new in this respect? 
  [Baraq] There is no news; however, we will continue doing 
everything that may contribute to the discovery of new 
information about the fate of the MIA's and to return the POW's 
home. [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

