<H3> <TI>   NATO `Air Display' in Bosnia Seen `Humiliating' Russia </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    NATO `Air Display' in Bosnia Seen `Humiliating' Russia </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1404142694 Tehran Voice of the Islamic Republic of Iran 
First Program Network in Persian 0953 GMT 14 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1404142694 </F>
<F P=104>  Tehran Voice of the Islamic Republic of Iran 
First Program Network </F>

<F P=105>  Persian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Unattributed commentary] </F>
  [Excerpts] The NATO air attack on Serb positions last 
Monday, with the objective of forcing them to respect Gorazde as 
a UN declared safe haven, will undoubtedly affect the stand of 
all the warring sides and the influential foreign states. It is 
said that the U.S. Government wishes to continue such attacks 
from time to time, for the Serb aggression against Gorazde has 
wiped off the United Nations' last vestige of prestige and has 
undermined the Security Council decisions, taken under the 
influence of the western governments. But it seems that NATO is 
the main loser of this international air display. 
  The NATO air raids, although limited to some sort of air 
display so far, has angered the Russians who were not consulted 
on the decision to launch an air strike. [passage omitted] 
  The extreme nationalists of the Russian legislatures, 
including Zhirinovskiy's Liberal Democratic Party, have now 
become the major faction influencing Russia's foreign policy. 
This faction does not wish to see further humiliation of 
Russia. They become angry when they see their Slav brothers are 
killed by the NATO bombs. The Russian Foreign Minister Andrey 
Kozyrev, therefore, protested and adopted a stand against the 
NATO air attack on the Serb positions. The attack foiled his 
dream of hoping that the West would consider Russia as an equal 
and trustworthy partner. The question in everybody's mind in 
Russia today is, when will the West stop humiliating Russia? 

</TEXT>

