<F P=100> Egypt </F>
<H3> <TI>   Minister on Dual Taxation Accords, State Budget </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Minister on Dual Taxation Accords, State Budget </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   NC1504104694 Cairo MENA in Arabic 0910 GMT 15 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> NC1504104694 </F>
<F P=104>  Cairo MENA </F>
<F P=105>  Arabic </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Cairo, 15 Apr (MENA)--Finance Minister Dr. Muhammad 
Ahmad al-Razzaz has said that 30 agreements have been signed 
with other countries to avoid dual taxation. 
  In a statement to MENA, he said discussion is under way to 
sign agreements between Egypt and Indonesia and Singapore on 
avoiding dual taxation to consolidate relations and economic 
ties. He added that the agreement concluded on Tuesday with the 
United Arab Emirates [UAE] and signed by the UAE minister of 
state for financial and industrial affairs, Ahmad Bin-Humayyid 
al-Tayir, is one of the most modern examples of agreements on 
avoiding dual taxation and dealing with every means of handling 
taxes on sources of income. 
  Al-Razzaz said the Finance Ministry will submit the draft 
state budget for 1994-95 to the People's Assembly at the end of 
April to be debated by the Assembly in May, adding that it will 
come into force on 1 July. 
  He said the preliminary estimates for the budget this year 
amount to 83 billion pounds and that the value of wages is 
approximately 12.8 billion pounds, a 2.2 billion-pound-increase 
on the current fiscal year, which ends at the end of June. The 
target budget deficit is 4.2 percent. Inflation is 2.8 percent 
and state revenues amount to 40.3 billion pounds, a 
15-percent-increase on the previous year. 

</TEXT>

