<F P=100> Morocco </F>
<H3> <TI>   Declaration Adopted at Uruguay Round Meeting </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Declaration Adopted at Uruguay Round Meeting </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Malaysian Minister Delivers Address </H4>

<F P=102> BK1404130094 Kuala Lumpur Voice of Malaysia in English 0600 
GMT 14 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> BK1404130094 </F>
<F P=104>  Kuala Lumpur Voice of Malaysia </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Malaysia will continue its unilateral 
liberalization policy in the financial services sector at a pace 
dictated by the national policy objectives to ensure foreign 
participation. International Trade and Industry Minister Datuk 
Sri Rafidah Aziz said Malaysia's offer of financial services was 
significant given the already high foreign presence in financial 
services sector. She said this was a result of Malaysia's 
unilateral liberalization measure, implemented even before the 
Uruguay Round talks. 
  She made those remarks at the Marrakech ministerial meeting 
on the Uruguay Round talks in Marrakech last night. About 120 
trade ministers from around the world have gathered in the 
Moroccan city to sign a landmark agreement on the final act of 
the trade talks, [words indistinct] of agreement. Malaysia 
[words indistinct] was committed to an open and strong 
multilateral trading system and attached much importance to 
[words indistinct] multilateral trade negotiations. Datuk Sri 
Rafidah said the conclusion of the Uruguay Round marked another 
important milestone in international economic cooperation and 
provided the foundation for strengthening an open trading 
system. It is a signal to the world that multilateral [words 
indistinct] is a universally acceptable trading norm and the 
successful conclusion of the Uruguay Round is indeed timely. 

</TEXT>

