<F P=100> IRAQ </F>
<H3> <TI>   `Deteriorating' U.S. Morale Blamed for Helicopter Incident </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    `Deteriorating' U.S. Morale Blamed for Helicopter Incident </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   JN1604081994 Baghdad INA in Arabic 0624 GMT 16 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> JN1604081994 </F>
<F P=104>  Baghdad INA </F>
<F P=105>  Arabic </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Baghdad, 16 Apr (INA)--AL-JUMHURIYAH has said that 
the American mindset, which accepts the unhesitating and hasty 
killing of the children of other peoples, is behind the shooting 
down of the two U.S. helicopters in northern Iraq. 
  In an article today on the downing of the two helicopters, 
the paper adds that deteriorating morale among U.S. officers, 
which is a traditional flaw in U.S. national security, makes 
them panic and act irrationally whenever they have doubts about 
the existence of an enemy force. U.S. propaganda and media 
incitement against Iraq added to the U.S. officers panic, thus 
making them act hastily, killing 26 Americans and Europeans, who 
they mistook for people of another nationality -- which would 
make it okay to kill them. 
  The paper adds: As in previous cases when he lied to 
Congress, Clinton this time tried to peddle another lie among 
the U.S. public to justify this incident and to contain any 
negative repercussions. He claimed that the dead were on a 
humanitarian mission assigned to them by the United Nations. 
However, the United Nations did not wait long to answer, 
immediately responding that it had nothing to do with the 
mission nor had it asked anybody to undertake this mission. 
The United Nations also said that the two helicopters received 
orders from the United States. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

