<F P=101> Algeria </F>
<H3> <TI>   Government Officially Asks Paris Club To Reschedule Debts </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Government Officially Asks Paris Club To Reschedule Debts </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1704203394 Algiers ENTV Television Network in Arabic 1900 
GMT 17 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1704203394 </F>
<F P=104>  Algiers ENTV Television Network </F>
<F P=105>  Arabic </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Excerpt] Algeria has officially asked the Paris Club to 
directly reschedule its foreign debts after signing the IMF 
letter of intent. These debts constitute of about 60 percent of 
its medium and long-term debts. Forthcoming talks with 
international banks will help reduce medium and long-term debt 
servicing. [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-13041 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drnes074_a_94005" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-NES-94-074 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  17 Apr 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> ARAB AFRICA </F>
<F P=101> Algeria </F>
<H3> <TI>   More on Debt Rescheduling </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    More on Debt Rescheduling </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1704231794 Algiers Radio Algiers Network in Arabic 2200 
GMT 17 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1704231794 </F>
<F P=104>  Algiers Radio Algiers Network </F>
<F P=105>  Arabic </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Algeria's Central Bank announced today that Algeria 
had officially contacted the Paris Club to reschedule its 
estimated 26-billion dollar foreign debt. 
  The same source clarified that the Paris Club debt 
rescheduling concerned bilateral debts which constitute 60 
percent of Algeria's medium and long-term debts. The bank added 
that indebtedness would decrease by 4 billion dollars during 
this year and by 5 billion dollars over the period of a standby 
agreement with the International Monetary Fund from April until 
March 1995. (Rachid Benhelmi) reports: 
  [Begin (Benhelmi) recording] Algeria's Central Bank 
statement 
said that the Paris Club had been contacted after signing a 
letter of intent with the IMF in order to reschedule Algeria's 
bilateral debts which constitute about 60 percent of total 
medium and long-term debts. They include loans granted and 
guaranteed by governments or creditors' governmental 
institutions. 
  According to the Bank of Algeria, negotiations will start 
soon with international banks to reschedule repayment dates for 
medium-term bank debts. 
  It is expected, according to experts, that the rescheduling 
of payments for bank debts would reduce debt servicing in the 
medium and long-term. 
  Running parallel to these negotiations, discussions with 
some 
multilateral institutions, particularly the World Bank, the 
African Development Bank, the Arab Monetary Fund, the European 
Community, and other main bodies dealing with Algeria -- like 
industrialists and traders -- would take place. It is expected 
that these discussions would lead to clinching additional 
financial reserves to cover requirements in foreign financing. 
  The short-term debts which should be repaid within one year 
or less would not be subject to rescheduling and their interest 
would be paid on time. [end recording] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-13042 </DOCNO>
