<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Arab-Israeli Talks </F>
<H3> <TI>   New Round of PLO-Israeli Talks Begins in Cairo </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    New Round of PLO-Israeli Talks Begins in Cairo </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Palestinian Official on 1st Session </H4>

<F P=102> NC1704164794 Cairo MENA in Arabic 1522 GMT 17 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> NC1704164794 </F>
<F P=104>  Cairo MENA </F>
<F P=105>  Arabic </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Cairo, 17 Apr (MENA)--Palestinian and Israeli 
negotiators meeting for talks to eliminate the obstacles 
impeding the implementation of the Gaza-Jericho accord on 
self-rule have wound up their first session, during which they 
continued the discussion of security issues. 
  Khalid al-Qidrah, a member of the Palestinian delegation, 
told MENA that the Security Affairs Committee held a two-hour 
meeting chaired on the Palestinian side by Brigadier General 
'Abd-al-Razzaq al-Yahya and on the Israeli side by Uzi Dayan, 
head of the Israeli Army's Planning Department. He added that 
the purpose of the meeting was to discuss issues concerning 
crossings between Gaza, Jericho, and Israel; joint 
Palestinian-Israeli patrols on parallel roads; the settlements' 
security; and other security topics. He said the Civil Affairs 
Committee, which will basically deal with water and 
communications, and the Legal Affairs Committee will meet later 
today. 
  Al-Qidrah said that during the previous round the Israeli 
side presented a working paper to the Palestinians on the legal 
jurisdiction in Gaza and Jericho. He affirmed that the paper 
has been rejected because it is not in line with the regional 
sovereignty of the self-rule authority. 
  He added that during this round the Palestinian side on the 
Legal Affairs Committee will submit a working paper on the legal 
and judicial jurisdiction and regional sovereignty. He noted 
that the Palestinian side demands full jurisdiction and 
sovereignty over the Palestinian territories. 
  He said: The Israeli paper, which was presented to us at the 
end of the last round, was not discussed. He affirmed that the 
Palestinian side rejected it completely. 
  Al-Qidrah rejected Israel having any legal jurisdiction in 
Gaza and Jericho, even on non-Palestinians as long as they are 
present in the territories under the Palestinian self-rule 
authority, noting that the Israeli proposal is incompatible with 
international law. 
  This round of negotiations, which opened this morning, is 
expected to last until Thursday. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-13048 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drnes074yy_94003" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-NES-94-074 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  18 Apr 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Arab-Israeli Talks </F>
<H3> <TI>   New Round of PLO-Israeli Talks Begins in Cairo </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    New Round of PLO-Israeli Talks Begins in Cairo </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Talks Continue; Sha'th Notes Agenda </H4>

<F P=102> NC1804061894 Cairo Arab Republic of Egypt Radio Network in 
Arabic 0500 GMT 18 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> NC1804061894 </F>
<F P=104>  Cairo Arab Republic of Egypt Radio Network </F>
<F P=105>  Arabic </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Palestinian and Israeli negotiators will today 
continue the talks they began in Cairo yesterday. The talks aim 
to resolve some unsettled issues concerning the implementation 
of the Gaza-Jericho agreement. 
  Nabil Sha'th, head of the Palestinian delegation, said the 
current talks focus on the release of detained Palestinians, 
crossing points between both Gaza and Jericho and Israel, and 
joint Palestinian-Israeli patrols. Sha'th added that any delay 
in the implementation of the Declaration of Principles will 
increase the suffering of the Palestinian people in the occupied 
territories. He expressed hopes of progress in the current 
round of talks, which will last until the end of this week. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

