<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-NES-94-074 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  17 Apr 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Arab-Israeli Talks </F>
<H3> <TI>   Multilateral Talks on Water Begin in Oman </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Multilateral Talks on Water Begin in Oman </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Talks Open With Call for Stable Supplies </H4>

<F P=102> NC1704100594 Paris AFP in English 0838 GMT 17 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> NC1704100594 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Nadim Ka'wash] </F>
  [Text] Muscat, April 17 (AFP) - Officials from Israel, Arab 
states, and other countries and organisations opened talks on 
water resources here Sunday [17 April] with a call by Oman for 
an agreement to ensure stable supplies. 
  Omani Minister of State for Foreign Affairs Yusuf Ibn-'Alawi 
Bin-'Abdallah said water was one of the most important issues 
being negotiated in the region, as he opened the session at 
Muscat's Intercontinental Hotel. 
  Social and economic development plans required an agreement 
among all the countries of the Middle East to manage water 
resources and develop secure and stable supplies, he told the 
participants. 
  Deputy Foreign Minister Yosi Beilin was heading the Israeli 
delegation at the talks, due to last four days. It is the first 
ever visit to a Gulf Arab state by Israeli officials. 
  The water committee is one of five set up within the 
framework of the Middle East peace negotiations. 
  The talks on water resources are the first to take place in 
a 
Gulf country. It is the fifth session since the multilateral 
meetings began, following the 1991 Madrid peace conference. 
  "We had not expected such hospitality and warmth here," said 
a member of the Israeli delegation of more than 15 officials, 
accompanied by 20 journalists. "We are really impressed." 
  Another Israeli delegate said he had "the impression that 
the 
barriers between all the people of the region could come down 
and we can become friends." 
  Beilin met the head of the Omani delegation on Saturday to 
discuss the agenda of the meeting. 
  Conference sources said the Israeli delegation had 
threatened 
to boycott the meeting following a Palestinian delegate's 
statement that the PLO and Israel had agreed to set up a 
National Palestinian Committee to manage Palestinian water 
resources. 
  "The Palestinian delegate later corrected his statement and 
said the committee was part of the autonomy agreement. His 
earlier comments implied a Palestinian state", said an Israeli 
journalist who spoke to Beilin. 
  The Israelis are also due to attend a meeting on arms 
control 
in Qatar early next month, and a tourism conference in Dubai 
this year, officials said. 
  'Alawi said Oman had finalised studies with international 
help to upgrade water desalination facilities. The studies were 
presented to the meeting. 
  "We hope this effort will be a successful beginning for 
serious research to develop water desalination," he said. 
  "Such an achievement will also contribute greatly to 
preventing the danger of potential conflict over water 
resources. There is no doubt such a trend requires joint 
cooperation, especially with industrialised countries which have 
the experience and technology in this field". 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-13053 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drnes074yy_94008" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-NES-94-074 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  17 Apr 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Arab-Israeli Talks </F>
<H3> <TI>   Multilateral Talks on Water Begin in Oman </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Multilateral Talks on Water Begin in Oman </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Oman's Bin-'Alawi Addresses Conference </H4>

<F P=102> JN1704160994 Muscat Radio Oman Network in Arabic 1300 GMT 17 
Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> JN1704160994 </F>
<F P=104>  Muscat Radio Oman Network </F>
<F P=105>  Arabic </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] His Excellency Yusuf Bin-'Alawi Bin-'Abdallah, Omani 
minister of state for foreign affairs, has opened the fifth 
meeting of the water committee within the multilateral talks 
stemming from the Middle East peace conference. The conference, 
which was opened at the Muscat Intercontinental Hotel this 
morning, is attended by 42 states, in addition to the Sultanate 
of Oman, and three international organizations -- the United 
Nations, the European Union, and the World Bank. 
  At the beginning of the four-day meeting, His Excellency 
Yusuf Bin-'Alawi Bin-'Abdallah delivered a speech in which he 
said: As the Sultanate of Oman today hosts the meeting of the 
water resources group within the multilateral talks of the 
Middle East peace conference, it strongly expresses its firm 
conviction of the importance of continuing the march of peace. 
  His excellency added that the sultanate's support for the 
peace process in the Middle East is based on a longstanding 
conviction that resolving the Middle East problem and its crux, 
the Palestinian cause, can only be achieved through direct 
dialogue and serious talks among the involved parties. 
  His excellency stressed that the convening of this meeting 
reflects the concern of the participant states in continuing 
their support and their valuable contribution to support the 
peace process. At the same time, he added, the meeting is an 
opportunity for the delegations to continue their constructive 
discussion, which they began in previous meetings, regarding 
water problems in the Middle East. 
  His excellency the minister of state for foreign affairs 
said: The multilateral track of the peace process concentrates 
on the details. We, in the water group, however, aim at 
preserving the scarce sources of water resources and concentrate 
on the importance of developing and creating new techniques in 
the service of water. We must realize that the work done by the 
water resources group is one of the most important factors of 
cooperation among the Middle East countries for many essential 
reasons, the most important of which is the limited water 
resources in the region. Therefore, the plans for social and 
economic development require that all Middle Eastern countries 
agree on policies to manage water resources and distribution and 
to secure stable water supplies. 
  His excellency said: In light of this, the Sultanate of Oman 
carried out a comprehensive survey to learn about the standards 
reached by water desalination research and technology in the 
world, which it was charged with by the committee during the 
Beijing meeting, to lay down options to reduce the financial 
burdens resulting from water desalination. 
  His excellency said: The document, which will be presented 
to you and which was the production of this survey, represents a 
distinguished technical achievement by a group specialized 
experts and is the result of positive common work thanks to the 
valuable cooperation demonstrated by your countries. 
  He added: On this occasion, we would like to express our 
heartfelt appreciation to those experts and to all those 
countries who contributed to the success of this study, which 
has come up with specific proposals and recommendations which 
will be detailed by the Omani delegation participating in this 
meeting. 
  The minister of state for foreign affairs expressed hope 
that 
this effort will be a successful beginning for serious 
scientific research to develop water desalination technology so 
that it will be used in ways that will have positive effects on 
the economic development in the Middle East. His excellency 
noted that such an achievement will also largely contribute to 
curbing the danger of potential conflict over water resources. 
He added that this trend requires constructive collective 
cooperation, especially with advanced industrialized countries 
that have genuine experience in this regard. 
  His excellency said: We have passed the stage in which we 
considered the mere holding of a meeting between us an 
achievement. We are aware of the fact that these very important 
multilateral meetings should be in harmony with what is achieved 
in the bilateral tracks of the peace talks by laying down sound 
foundations for tangible cooperation over mutual interests and 
common views regarding the issues of the region, which are the 
main topics of the multilateral talks. 
  His Excellency Yusuf Bin-'Alawi Bin-'Abdallah stressed that 
participants from the region know full well that we have made a 
progress in this peace process and reached the threshold of a 
new stage that requires initiatives aimed at building bridges 
and achieving interconnection among the partners of peace. 
Therefore, the multilateral working groups and committees 
should work to reinforce their role and efficiency to support 
the bilateral track of the peace process and to continue to lay 
down practical plans and views that will achieve common benefits 
for all parties in an atmosphere of peace and stability. 

</TEXT>

