<F P=100> India </F>
<H3> <TI>   Officials, Parties React to Signing of GATT Accord </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Officials, Parties React to Signing of GATT Accord </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Other `Mixed Reaction' Noted </H4>

<F P=102> BK1604110494 Delhi All India Radio Network in English 0245 
GMT 16 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> BK1604110494 </F>
<F P=104>  Delhi All India Radio Network </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] The signing of the GATT by India at Marrakesh has 
evoked mixed reaction. The former prime minister and the 
Samajwadi Janata Party leader, Mr. Chandra Shekhar, has 
criticized the signing of the GATT adopting Dunkel proposals by 
India. Addressing public meetings at Chandigarh, Ludhiana and 
Amritsar yesterday, Mr. Chandra Shekhar said these proposals 
will badly affect and erode the Indian values swadeshi 
[indigenousness] and self-sufficiency as propounded by Mahatama 
Gandhi and other leaders. 
  Reacting to the signing of GATT by the government, the Uttar 
Pradesh chief minister, Mulayam Singh Yadav, said the people 
should have been taken into confidence before signing it. He 
said the chief ministers should have been consulted before 
signing the agreement which would affect the national interests. 
The Bihar chief minister, Mr. Lalu Prasad Yadav, addressing a 
public meeting at Sopol, charged the Congress-I with selling out 
the country's sovereignty by signing the agreement. 
  The BJP [Bharatiya Janata Party] yesterday observed a 
protest 
day in Madhya Pradesh against the signing of GATT, while the 
Communist Party of India-Marxist observed the black day in the 
state. Janata Dal workers held demonstrations in some towns of 
Uttar Pradesh. However, the Congress-I has welcomed the signing 
of agreement by India and charged the Opposition with indulging 
in a disinformation campaign on the issue. Speaking to 
reporters in New Delhi yesterday, the party spokesman, Mr. V.N. 
Gadgil, said the agreement will boost India's agricultural and 
textile exports. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

