<F P=100> India </F>
<H3> <TI>   `Official Sources' Say No Change in NPT Stand </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    `Official Sources' Say No Change in NPT Stand </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   BK1704160994 Delhi All India Radio Network in English 1530 
GMT 17 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> BK1704160994 </F>
<F P=104>  Delhi All India Radio Network </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Official sources in New Delhi have clarified that 
there is no change in India's stand on Nuclear Nonproliferation 
Treaty [NPT]. New Delhi believes that nuclear nonproliferation 
must be universal, comprehensive, and nondiscriminatory. The 
sources said the prime minister had categorically stated this 
position in his recent address to the Army commanders 
conference. They were reacting to press reports that the BJP 
[Bharatiya Janata Party] leader, Mr. Atal behari Vajpayee, 
expressed the view that the prime minister's observations over 
the issue needs clarification. 
  The sources said Mr. Narasimha Rao in his speech made it 
clear that any attempt to restrict India's nuclear option will 
be unacceptable and unrealistic in view of Pakistan having 
acquired nuclear weapon capability. There is also proliferation 
of such weapons recently. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

