<F P=100> Egypt </F>
<H3> <TI>   Mubarak's Envoy to Liberia Reports on Mission </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Mubarak's Envoy to Liberia Reports on Mission </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   NC1704132194 Cairo MENA in Arabic 1245 GMT 17 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> NC1704132194 </F>
<F P=104>  Cairo MENA </F>
<F P=105>  Arabic </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Cairo, 17 Apr (MENA) -- Foreign Minister 'Amr Musa 
today received a report from Assistant Foreign Minister 
Ambassador Sa'id Rif'at on the mission he undertook in Liberia 
as President Husni Mubarak's envoy. 
  Ambassador Rif'at stated that President Mubarak entrusted 
him 
with a message to the Liberian State Council, reflecting his 
interest in the situation in Liberia after the various parties 
signed a peace agreement. The mission was within the context of 
Egyptian efforts to settle the Liberian problem and its backing 
for the State Council, the transitional government, and 
constitutional measures. 
  Ambassador Rif'at added that during his visit to Liberia he 
met the State Council members and discussed developments in the 
Liberian problem and ways to settle it, with particular emphasis 
on disarming the factions and completing the formation of the 
transitional government. 
  He pointed out that the Liberian parties reiterated their 
eagerness to find a settlement and form a government. The 
Liberian powers expressed their appreciation of the Egyptian 
role and reiterated their desire to see Egypt contributing to 
the country's reconstruction once the peace agreement is 
implemented, he said. 
  Rif'at added that he assured Liberian officials of Egypt's 
preparedness to offer its expertise in development and to extend 
training assistance to Liberians in medicine, engineering, and 
nursing. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

