<F P=100> Egypt </F>
<H3> <TI>   Inter-Arab Trade, Common Market Viewed </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Inter-Arab Trade, Common Market Viewed </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   NC1704122094 Cairo MENA in Arabic 1110 GMT 17 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> NC1704122094 </F>
<F P=104>  Cairo MENA </F>
<F P=105>  Arabic </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Cairo, 17 Apr (MENA)--Mahmud al-'Arabi, chairman of 
the General Federation of the Chambers of Commerce, has stated 
that the Arab common market can withstand no delay, particularly 
in view of world economic developments and the ongoing 
competition to set up free trade areas and attract investment. 
  In a statement today, al-'Arabi pointed out that inter-Arab 
trade today represents under 12 percent of collective Arab 
foreign trade. He noted that Arab investments in the Arab world 
are limited, although over $850 billion is being invested 
elsewhere. He called for adopting positive measures to attract 
part of the Arab capital being invested in foreign states. 
  Al-'Arabi pointed out that the necessary foundation for a 
common Arab market exists but that it needs a set of measures to 
be perfected. He explained that the required measures are to 
facilitate the movement of goods and flow of trade among Arab 
states, reduce shipping charges, eliminate customs barriers, and 
encourage bilateral agreements as a basis for a common Arab 
market. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

