<F P=100> ISRAEL </F>
<H3> <TI>   Update on Contacts With Syria, Jordan </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Update on Contacts With Syria, Jordan </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   TA1704065194 Jerusalem Qol Yisra'el in English 0400 GMT 17 
Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> TA1704065194 </F>
<F P=104>  Jerusalem Qol Yisra'el </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Excerpts] Prime Minister Yitzhaq Rabin says that without 
secret talks with Syria, a peace agreement cannot be reached. 
In an interview with the Cairo newspaper AL-AHRAM, Rabin says 
Israel had tried to arrange secret meetings with Syrian leaders, 
but they had refused. In the interview, Rabin accused Syria of 
talking peace, while simultaneously supporting Palestinian 
organizations opposed to negotiations. 
  Major General Ilan Biran, who today takes over as the head 
of 
the IDF [Israel Defense Forces] Central Command, has presented 
Prime Minister Rabin with a working paper on security 
arrangements on the Golan. Biran discussed the issue with the 
prime minister and with Chief of Staff Baraq on Friday and on a 
previous occasion. [passage omitted] 
  [Jerusalem Qol Yisra'el in Hebrew at 0500 GMT on 17 April 
reports: "Israel has expressed its displeasure over the harsh 
criticism Syria had leveled at Oman for its willingness to host 
an Israeli delegation. Our correspondent in Washington Arye 
Golan reports that Professor Itamar Rabinovich, Israel's 
ambassador to the United States, spoke to U.S. coordinator 
Dennis Ross on the matter, and told him that the Syrian remarks 
do not contribute to the establishment of a proper atmosphere in 
view of the upcoming Middle East tour by U.S. Secretary of State 
Warren Christopher, and toward the resumption of the peace 
talks."] 
  The Prime Minister's office in Jerusalem says there were 
contacts involving Syria, after katyusha rockets landed in 
Israel, during the early hours of Friday morning. Jerusalem 
says those contacts brought quiet to the Israeli side of the 
border over the Sabbath, even if katyushas did land in southern 
Lebanon. 
  [Tel Aviv YEDI'OT AHARONOT in Hebrew on 17 April carries a 
report by Ron Ben-Yishay on pages 1 and 15, adding: "Over the 
weekend, the Israeli Government relayed a warning to Hizballah 
and Syria that if murderous attacks on the SLA [South Lebanese 
Army] and Lebanese civilians in the security zone continue, the 
IDF will feel free to ignore the understandings made after 
Operation Accountability last summer." The report adds that 
"there is growing concern among Israel's top security echelons 
that the SLA might gradually disintegrate, physically and 
morally, and that the security zone in south Lebanon might 
crumble."] 
  Also at the Prime Minister's Office, there is expectation 
for 
more progress with the PLO on Gaza-Jericho first, as the 
Israelis prepare for the resumption of those talks today. If 
the Palestinians raise the issue of the closure of the 
territories imposed a week and a half ago, an official in 
Jerusalem said last night they will be told that the possibility 
of lifting restrictions has been and will continue to be checked 
on a constant basis, including at this morning's cabinet meeting. 
  There is no reaction in Jerusalem to King Husayn's news 
conference on Hamas. Prime Minister Rabin's media adviser 'Oded 
Ben-'Ami says Israel will know whether in fact Jordan has acted 
against Hamas operations in the country, based on whether or not 
we hear from the Hamas people in Jordan again. For now, says 
Ben-'Ami, we have said what we wanted to say. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

