<F P=100> ISRAEL </F>
<H3> <TI>   Plan Envisions Full Withdrawal From Golan </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Plan Envisions Full Withdrawal From Golan </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   TA1804083194 Tel Aviv HA'ARETZ in Hebrew 18 Apr 94 pp A1, A8 </F>
<F P=103> TA1804083194 </F>
<F P=104>  Tel Aviv HA'ARETZ </F>
<F P=105>  Hebrew </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by political correspondent Aluf Ben and 'Aqiva Eldar] </F>
  [Excerpts] In the past few weeks, a state body subject to 
the Prime Minister's Office presented Prime Minister Yitzhaq 
Rabin with a plan for a peace arrangement with Syria. The paper 
was drafted in parallel with similar work done by the IDF 
[Israel Defense Forces] and the Foreign Ministry. 
  The plan, drafted at the initiative of that body's research 
department, assumes that, in the framework of the agreement, 
there will be a total Israeli withdrawal from the Golan Heights 
and that the negotiations with Syria will focus on security 
arrangements and stages of normalization and withdrawal. 
  The authors of the document propose a staged withdrawal over 
a period of more than 10 years, during which the IDF will 
maintain its military presence on the Golan. They believe that 
future peace relations between Israel and Syria will be similar 
to those existing between Israel and Egypt -- perhaps even 
cooler. 
  The team that drafted the document on the arrangement with 
Syria prepared a proposal four months ago on an arrangement with 
the Palestinians. That paper determined that the preferable 
solution for Israel is the establishment of a 
Jordanian-Palestinian confederation. 
  Of the three staff works prepared in anticipation of the 
resumption of the negotiations with Syria, only the one prepared 
by Major General Ilan Biran was done by order of the prime 
minister and followed his guidance regarding the principles of 
the arrangement. Biran's paper speaks of a withdrawal on the 
Golan Heights, but not a full one. The Foreign Ministry and the 
state body, which assumed that a full withdrawal will be carried 
out, based their work on their own assumptions. [passage 
omitted] 
  As U.S. Secretary of State Warren Christopher's tour of the 
Middle East approaches, Israeli sources in Washington have 
reported that Israel will not relay detailed plans on peace 
arrangements and a withdrawal to Syria through the United 
States. The prime minister will again ask the secretary of 
state to propose to Syria to begin a practical discussion of the 
security arrangements, but it is not clear whether al-Asad will 
accept this proposal and waive his demand that Israel pledge a 
full withdrawal in advance. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

