<F P=100> Palestinian Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   'Abbas Discusses Differences in Cairo Talks </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    'Abbas Discusses Differences in Cairo Talks </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   NC1804085394 Cairo Voice of the Arabs in Arabic 0610 GMT 18 
Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> NC1804085394 </F>
<F P=104>  Cairo Voice of the Arabs </F>
<F P=105>  Arabic </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Telephone interview with Mahmud 'Abbas, member of the PLO </F>
Executive Committee, in Tunis, by Ashraf 'Abd-al-'Aziz, in 
Cairo, date not given; from the "Dialogue From Afar" program -- 
live or recorded] 
  [Text] ['Abd-al-'Aziz] Welcome to our program. 
  ['Abbas] Thank you. 
  ['Abd-al-'Aziz] A new round of Palestinian-Israeli talks has 
started in Cairo over the implementation of the Gaza-Jericho 
agreement. The Economic Affairs Committee also resumed its work 
in Paris. What have these talks achieved? 
  ['Abbas] Significant progress has been achieved in the 
latest 
round of talks in Cairo. The two sides worked out full details 
concerning the police force. This topic is now closed. Once 
the signal is given, the police force will be ready to deploy. 
The issue has been fully discussed. 
  The talks in Cairo also focused on the civilian [local 
administration] functions. Only one of these functions needs 
further discussion. The current round of talks may finalize 
this issue as well. 
  Economic issues are being discussed in Paris. Economic 
issues, we all know, are numerous and complicated. At issue are 
concerns such as customs, taxes, trade, merchandise, labor, and 
currency. I can say there has been some 90-percent progress in 
this regard. I expect that issues concerning both the economy 
and the civilian administration will be resolved in the current 
round of talks. 
  If some issues remain unsettled, the two sides will decide 
whether to hold further negotiations to resolve them or begin 
implementing the agreement immediately It all depends on what 
the two sides will agree upon. 
  ['Abd-al-'Aziz] What are the most important of the 
unresolved 
issues? 
  ['Abbas] They have to do with security, the crossings, 
geographic jurisdiction, and the judiciary. There are quite a 
few snags here and there and although we cannot shrug them off, 
I think it is advisable to begin the implementation and let the 
talks go on. This is what we plan to tell the Israelis. 
  ['Abd-al-'Aziz] What is the real cause of the remaining 
differences between the Palestinians and Israelis? 
  ['Abbas] It has to do with the interpretation of the 
Declaration of Principles. Every side is trying to interpret it 
in the way that suits them, to tell you the truth. The 
Declaration of Principles is a document that needs 
interpretation and clarification and gives rise to differing 
views and a bit of horse-trading. This is the reason for the 
differences. 
  Naturally, the Israelis want to hold on to the land and the 
authority they have until the very last. They find it hard to 
let go. 
  ['Abd-al-'Aziz] The recent incidents in the occupied 
territories have proven that Israel's security claims are unreal 
and that there is a need for Palestinian security as well. 
  ['Abbas] I hope the Israelis will understand this, namely, 
that both the Israelis and Palestinians need security. I hope 
the Israelis will also understand that the issue is actually one 
of confidence, not security. We are discussing peace. If we 
have genuine intentions of making peace, real security and other 
measures will certainly be taken without reference to texts. 
  ['Abd-al-'Aziz] Recent Israeli statements say the 
Palestinian-Israeli Agreement will be signed soon. Is this true? 
  ['Abbas] I cannot give dates or depend on dates. I say that 
when work on the basic and necessary files is completed, the two 
sides will be ready for signing and implementation. There is 
another point: The two sides may finish with some files and 
agree to begin implementation while negotiations on the 
remaining files continue. This is decided through negotiations. 
But we cannot say the signing will be tomorrow, the day after, 
next week, or in two weeks. A single word or minor problem may 
obstruct the signing. We cannot give people false hopes that 
may not be fulfilled. 
  ['Abd-al-'Aziz] Should we expect a summit meeting between 
Palestinian president Yasir 'Arafat and Israeli Prime Minister 
Yitzhaq Rabin very soon? 
  ['Abbas] When a summit is decided, it will mean the 
implementation of the agreement has started. Such a summit will 
be meant to announce the implementation, not to hold 
negotiations. 
  ['Abd-al-'Aziz] Mahmud 'Abbas: The file of the Palestinian 
police force was closed after an agreement was reached. Is the 
force prepared to assume security on the Palestinian territory? 
  ['Abbas] Yes. Of course. The force will be ready. It is. 
When it enters Palestinian territory, it will start assuming its 
national responsibilities on its land. 
  ['Abd-al-'Aziz] This is my last question. The multilateral 
talks on water are now being held in Muscat, Oman. A 
Palestinian delegation is participating. What are the 
Palestinian proposals at these talks? 
  ['Abbas] We make no Palestinian proposals. We make Arab 
ones. We cooperate with the Arab brothers taking part in these 
negotiations. The water issue is of concern not only to the 
Palestinians, but to all Arab sides in the Middle East. Any 
views we may offer, therefore, must be in harmony with the views 
of our brothers who are attending the talks or are concerned 
with this issue. 
  ['Abd-al-'Aziz] Thank you. 
  ['Abbas] You are welcome. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-13175 </DOCNO>
