<F P=100> India </F>
<H3> <TI>   Officials, Parties React to Signing of GATT Accord </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Officials, Parties React to Signing of GATT Accord </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Congress-I Welcomes Signing </H4>

<F P=102> BK1504162694 Delhi All India Radio Network in English 1530 
GMT 15 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> BK1504162694 </F>
<F P=104>  Delhi All India Radio Network </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] The Congress-I has welcomed the signing of the new 
GATT accord by India at Marrakech and charged the opposition 
with indulging in a disinformation campaign on the issue. 
Speaking to reporters in New Delhi today, the party spokesman, 
Mr. V.N. Gadgil, said the agreement will boost India's 
agricultural and textile exports. He said the government will 
now have to translate the agreement into various laws and these 
have to come before parliament. 
  The minister of state for commerce, Mr. Kamaluddin Ahmad, 
said that the new agreement is on the whole beneficial to India. 
Speaking to a group of foreign journalists in New Delhi today, 
he reaffirmed India's faith in a rule-based transparent 
multilateral trading system. 
  The BJP [Bharatiya Janata Party] president, Mr. L.K. Advani, 
has criticized the signing of the Marrakech Declaration by 
India. He said in New Delhi that the treaty has been conceived 
by developed countries to promote their trade interests. 

</TEXT>

