<F P=100> LEBANON </F>
<H3> <TI>   Severing Relations Considered </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Severing Relations Considered </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PM1504122194 London AL-SHARQ AL-AWSAT in Arabic 15 Apr 94 pp 
1, 4 </F>

<F P=103> PM1504122194 </F>
<F P=104>  London AL-SHARQ AL-AWSAT </F>
<F P=105>  Arabic </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Unattributed report: "Lebanon Hints at Severing Relations </F>
With Iraq"] 
  [Excerpts] London-Beirut-Amman, AL-SHARQ AL-AWSAT -- 
Yesterday the Lebanese Government officially requested that Iraq 
lift the immunity of Iraqi diplomats Khalid Kahalaf and Muhammad 
Kazim, who are accused of assassinating Iraqi oppositionist 
Talib Suhayl in Beirut the day before yesterday evening. It 
also turned down a request submitted by the Iraqi Embassy in 
Beirut that the two detained diplomats be released, saying that 
they are under "guard" for their own safety and investigation 
requirements. [passage omitted] 
  Official Lebanese sources told AL-SHARQ AL-AWSAT yesterday 
that, if the Lebanese Government receives a negative response to 
its request that the immunity of the two detained diplomats be 
lifted and that the third man accused of the crime be handed 
over, it could decide to sever diplomatic relations with Baghdad. 
  The sources added that a decision would be made after 
consultation with Charge D'Affaires Sa'd Zakhya, the only 
Lebanese diplomat in Baghdad, who was summoned by the Lebanese 
Foreign Ministry for "consultation." The Lebanese sources added 
that, if Baghdad refuses to lift the immunity of the detained 
culture and trade attaches, they would be declared persona non 
grata and expelled from Lebanese territory. [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

