<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Arab-Israeli Talks </F>
<H3> <TI>   PLO, Israeli Negotiators Continue Cairo Meetings </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    PLO, Israeli Negotiators Continue Cairo Meetings </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Sha'th Assails Rabin Over Delays </H4>

<F P=102> JN1804172894 London AL-HAYAH in Arabic 14 Apr 94 p 6 </F>
<F P=103> JN1804172894 </F>
<F P=104>  London AL-HAYAH </F>
<F P=105>  Arabic </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Muhammad 'Allam in Cairo] </F>
  [Text] Chief Palestinian negotiator Dr. Nabil Sha'th has 
warned that he who does respect the dates in the agreements that 
he has signed does not adhere to the texts of these agreements, 
and accused Israeli Prime Minister Yitzhaq Rabin of going too 
far in his attempt to ignore the dates, saying this violates the 
commitments by which we are determined to abide. 
  Sha'th told AL-HAYAH that any agreement takes place between 
two sides, and we should reach an agreement within two or three 
weeks at most. [sentence as published] 
  He expressed the Palestinian side's fear that Rabin may 
delay 
the deadline from 15 May to a later date, and said: We are 
supposed to fix a date and to stick to it. 
  Sha'th reiterated the call on the U.S. Administration to pay 
its role as a sponsor of the peace process, and to adhere to its 
stated positions, and said: We are determined to continue the 
negotiations. 
  He described U.S. Secretary of State Warren Christopher's 
expected visit to the region later this month as important. 
  On the Hadera operation that took place yesterday, he said: 
It is painful that actions of killing in Gaza, Hebron, 'Afula, 
and Hadera continue and that innocents, whether they are 
Palestinians or Israelis, are killed without any reason other 
than that no applicable just peace has been reached. 
  He said the operation should encourage an expedited peace 
agreement in order to protect the innocents on both sides. 
  Answering a question on a statement by Military Intelligence 
Commander General Uri in which he said negotiating delegation 
members Muhammad Dahlan and Faysal al-Husayni, among others, are 
nominees to replace Palestinian President 'Arafat, Sha'th 
accused Israel of trying to instigate differences among the 
Palestinian personalities and said: This is no more than an 
attempt to instigate 'Arafat in an exposed and lowly manner 
against his men. 
  Sha'th denied that there is agreement with Israel on 
supplying the Palestinian police with six helicopters, two of 
which will be placed at the disposal of President 'Arafat, and 
said: There is no such agreement. 
  He denied that there is a plan to convene a meeting between 
'Arafat and Israeli Foreign Minister Shim'on Peres in Bucharest 
tomorrow. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-13190 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drnes075yy_94002" </HT>


<HEADER>
