<DATE1>  16 Apr 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Arab-Israeli Talks </F>
<H3> <TI>   PLO, Israeli Negotiators Continue Cairo Meetings </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    PLO, Israeli Negotiators Continue Cairo Meetings </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Sha'th: 30,000 To Enter Gaza, Jericho </H4>

<F P=102> JN1604203894 Sanaa Voice of Palestine in Arabic 1800 GMT 16 
Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> JN1604203894 </F>
<F P=104>  Sanaa Voice of Palestine </F>
<F P=105>  Arabic </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Nabil Sha'th, chief Palestinian negotiator to the 
PLO-Israeli talks, has said that within a week of the signing of 
the Gaza-Jericho agreement 6,500-7,000 military and police 
personnel will enter Gaza and Jericho as the backbone of a 
Palestinian security force. 
  In statements to the Egyptian daily AL-AHRAM published 
[words 
indistinct] that considering that their families will accompany 
them, a total of 30,000 Palestinians will enter Gaza and Jericho 
within a week. Most of these, he noted, belong to the refugees 
who were displaced in 1948. Together with them will also enter 
the entire political Palestinian leadership [passage indistinct] 
to look into the return of the persons displaced in 1967. 
  Sha'th emphasized that the presence of a national authority 
inside will lead to the institution of some symbols of 
sovereignty like measures related to economic development. He 
indicated that the donor countries that have decided to 
contribute financial grants toward the development of Gaza and 
Jericho are waiting for the signing of the accord and the 
installation of the Palestinian authority. Economic development 
and water, he said, will be the most pressing issues for the 
Palestinian authority. If a solution is not found to the water 
issue, there will be a retrenchment in the agricultural sector. 
We will rely more heavily on pollution free modern technology, 
tourism, and trade, said Sha'th. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

