<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Arab-Israeli Talks </F>
<H3> <TI>   PLO, Israeli Negotiators Continue Cairo Meetings </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    PLO, Israeli Negotiators Continue Cairo Meetings </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Remarks by `Sources' Cited </H4>

<F P=102> NC1804111394 Cairo MENA in Arabic 0930 GMT 18 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> NC1804111394 </F>
<F P=104>  Cairo MENA </F>
<F P=105>  Arabic </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Cairo, 18 Apr (MENA) -- Palestinian and Israeli 
negotiators resumed their meetings this morning with a meeting 
of the Security Committee cochaired by Major General 
'Abd-al-Razzaq Yahya and General Effin Agmon, deputy chief of 
the Israeli Army's planning department [name and title as 
received]. 
  General 'Uzi Dayan, chief of the Israeli Army's planning 
department, who was heading his country's delegation to the 
talks, left Cairo last night for a day in Israel. He is 
expected to return to Cairo tonight to join the talks. 
  According to Palestinian sources, the Legal Affairs 
Committee 
will resume its talks today. The committee will examine two 
working papers, a Palestinian and an Israeli, concerning the 
legal and judicial powers of the Palestinian authorities in the 
self-rule areas. 
  Khalid al-Qidrah, a member of the Palestinian negotiating 
team, yesterday told MENA that the paper Israel presented at the 
end of the last round is "completely unacceptable." 
  According to Palestinian sources, members of the Civilian 
Affairs Committee will meet today in subcommittees to discuss 
water, communications, and other unresolved issues. Experts 
from both sides will attend the meetings of the subcommittee on 
water, the same sources said. 
  The subcommittee on communications will mainly discuss the 
frequencies that the Palestinian authorities will use for 
police, communications, and other purposes. The two sides 
agreed on measures concerning the creation of a Palestinian 
radio and television service, according to the same sources. 
  The Palestinian sources said that a subcommittee emanating 
from the Legal Affairs Committee will begin working today on the 
draft of a final agreement. The same sources said that it is 
too early to speak of progress in the talks as they have just 
started. 
  Dr. Nabil Sha'th and General Amnon Shahaq, head of the 
Palestinian and Israeli delegations respectively, held a private 
meeting this morning in which they discussed issues concerning 
this round of talks, which will last until 21 April. 

</TEXT>

