<F P=100> Iran </F>
<H3> <TI>   President Receives Message From Bosnia's Izetbegovic </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    President Receives Message From Bosnia's Izetbegovic </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1804172394 Tehran IRIB Television First Program Network in 
Persian 1630 GMT 18 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1804172394 </F>
<F P=104>  Tehran IRIB Television First Program Network </F>
<F P=105>  Persian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Bosnia-Herzegovina President Alia Izetbegovic today 
sent a message to the president of our country from Sarajevo. 
The text of this message is as follows: 
  Your Excellency Akbar Hashemi-Rafsanjani, president of the 
Islamic Republic of Iran. 
  Dear Mr. President: I am sure that Your Excellency is aware 
of the tragedy that has befallen the inhabitants of Gorazde. 
The Serbian Army, which for the past two years, before the eyes 
of the world, has committed barbaric crimes in 
Bosnia-Herzegovina, is at the moment laying siege to a city that 
has 70,000 inhabitants, most of whom are women and children. 
The people of that city are desperately awaiting the assistance 
of international organizations. 
  Dear brother, at the most difficult and hard times, the 
Iranian people and Government have been with us and have helped 
us. Therefore, we will never feel alone. We are confident that 
you and the Government of the Islamic Republic of Iran will make 
every effort to defend the inhabitants of Gorazde and to prevent 
their destruction [soqut-e hasti], in view of the spiritual 
values which we adhere to. 
  Our faith and certainty in the brotherly assistance of Iran 
gives us the confidence to remain steadfast during these very 
critical moments. 
  May the merciful and compassionate God protect you with his 
blessings. With the most sincere greetings, 
  [Signed] Alia Izetbegovic 
  [Dated] 17 [as heard] April 1994, Sarajevo 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-13262 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drnes075_s_94004" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-NES-94-075 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  18 Apr 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> Iran </F>
<H3> <TI>   Speaks With Izetbegovic </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Speaks With Izetbegovic </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1804191794 Tehran IRIB Television Second Program Network 
in Persian 1800 GMT 18 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1804191794 </F>
<F P=104>  Tehran IRIB Television Second Program Network 
in Persian 1800 GMT 18 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=105> Persian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] President Hashemi-Rafsanjani spoke by phone with 
Bosnian President Alija Izetbegovic, and in response to his 
written mesage, talked about the latest situation in the 
conflict areas, especially in Gorazde. 
  In this telephone conversation, our president, referring to 
the deep sorrow of the officials and members of the public, from 
the esteemed leader of the Islamic Revolution down to the 
Government and the people of Iran, for the bitter and painful 
events of Bosnia, which are taking place in front of the 
indifferent eyes of the world, said: When the United Nations 
refused the offer of the Islamic Republic of Iran to dispatch 
forces to defend the people of Bosnia-Herzegovina and the areas 
that had been declared as safe havens by the same organization, 
the Iranian people realized that international organizations and 
countries are not serious in their claims of defending the 
defenseless people of Bosnia-Herzegovina. 
  The president added: Now that the United Nations has openly 
declared its inability to defend the wronged Bosnian nation, the 
Islamic Republic of Iran is prepared to send forces to the areas 
under the supervision of that organization and to defend the 
rights of the Muslim Bosnian people. Iran also welcomes the 
assistance of other countries. 
  Mr. Hashemi-Rafsanjani also asked the president of 
Bosnia-Herzegovina to convey the greetings and feelings of 
sympathy of the Iranian people to the oppressed Bosnian people. 
They should regard the Islamic Republic of Iran as a partner in 
their affliction and they should be assured that, as far as 
possible, the Iranian Government and people will not desert them 
in their struggle to achieve their legitimate rights. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-13263 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drnes075_s_94005" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-NES-94-075 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  19 Apr 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> Iran </F>
<H3> <TI>   Velayati Comments on Conversation With Butrus-Ghali </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Velayati Comments on Conversation With Butrus-Ghali </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   NC1904110194 Tehran Voice of the Islamic Republic of Iran 
First Program Network in Persian 0330 GMT 19 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> NC1904110194 </F>
<F P=104>  Tehran Voice of the Islamic Republic of Iran 
First Program Network </F>

<F P=105>  Persian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] The foreign minister contacted the UN secretary 
general by telephone last night and reiterated the Islamic 
Republic's readiness to dispatch forces to Bosnia. Velayati 
criticized the UN's policies and asked Butrus-Ghali: Is the 
fall of Gorazde not a prologue to the Serbs' attacks on other 
safe havens and the repetition of the Gorazde tragedy in vaster 
dimensions? 
  In answer to the criticisms by the Islamic Republic's 
foreign 
minister, the UN secretary general spoke about his efforts to 
solve the Bosnian problem, saying that he tried to encourage 
influential countries in the Security Council to defend Gorazde 
but that he failed. Butrus-Ghali promised to inform the 
Security Council of Iran's reiteration of its readiness to 
dispatch forces to Bosnia. 
  Minutes ago we contacted Velayati and asked him to comment 
on 
his contacts last night with the UN secretary general. Velayati 
said: Because of our repeated statements that we are ready to 
dispatch forces to Bosnia, Butrus-Ghali was mentally ready for 
this and promised that after holding talks with the Security 
Council members tonight he will inform us of the outcome of his 
steps concerning Iran's readiness to dispatch forces. 
  The second question we put to Velayati was: Two days ago the 
UN secretary general said that the only solution to the Bosnian 
problem is through talks. But in his remarks to you last night, 
he said that the Security Council members are not replying 
positively to his efforts for a military effort in Gorazde. 
There is a contradiction in these two stances. 
  In answer, Velayati described the future steps to be taken 
by 
our country as far as the Bosnian crisis is concerned: 
  [Begin Velayati recording] He [Butrus-Ghali] added last 
night that he has asked NATO to act but NATO has refrained. Of 
course, there is no doubt that the United Nations has displayed 
its inability in this field. Unfortunately, this organization 
and especially the Security Council has been transformed into a 
forum where big powers exercise their influence on it in order 
to fulfill their own intentions, and the innocent people in 
hotbeds become victims of the greed of influential powers in the 
Security Council. 
  Of course Mr. Butrus-Ghali has not used the power that the 
UN 
Charter has given him. On the basis of Article 99 of the UN 
Charter, when the Security Council is unable or unwilling to 
take a serious step to preserve world security and peace, the 
secretary general can use the UN tribune to call for help from 
world public opinion to overcome the specific problem that is 
threatening peace and security in some part of the world. But 
Mr. Butrus-Ghali has not made use of this power. 
  I told him last night: I want to know your opinion because 
after my conversation with you I intend to call the Islamic 
Conference Organization [ICO] secretary general and the 
Pakistani foreign minister who is the current president of the 
ICO and some others in order to organize the steps to be taken 
by Islamic countries. I want to know your opinion; and these 
are the next steps that we plan to take. 
  In tandem with our conversation, [Iranian UN representative] 
Dr. Kharrazi informed us from New York that he attended the 
contact group session there and that he proposed that the 
foreign ministers of the ICO contact group hold an emergency 
session in New York and call for presence in the Security 
Council to seriously discuss the issue at the Security Council. 
[end recording] 
  Minutes ago, IRNA reported from the United Nations that the 
UN secretary general discussed Iran's readiness to dispatch 
forces [to Bosnia] with Security Council members and that as 
usual, the Security Council did not make any decision on this. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-13264 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drnes075_s_94006" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-NES-94-075 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  18 Apr 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> Iran </F>
<H3> <TI>   Foreign Ministry Criticizes UN's `Inability' in Bosnia </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Foreign Ministry Criticizes UN's `Inability' in Bosnia </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1804175994 Tehran IRIB Television First Program Network in 
Persian 1630 GMT 18 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1804175994 </F>
<F P=104>  Tehran IRIB Television First Program Network </F>
<F P=105>  Persian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Our country's Foreign Ministry has issued a 
statement in the wake of the bestial attacks launched by the 
Serbs against the Muslim-inhabited town of Gorazde and the 
accompanying silence of the international forums. The statement 
criticizes the United Nations for holding back from forcing the 
Serbs to abide by the international regulations and accuses the 
United Nations of playing a part in the crimes committed by the 
Serbs in Bosnia-Herzegovina. 
  The statement says: Iran considers the United Nation's 
inability to carry out its duties as unjustifiable and once 
again calls on that organization's secretary general to accept 
the Islamic countries' proposal to dispatch troops to Bosnia and 
attempt to lift the arms embargo against that country's 
defenseless people, thus preventing the continuation of Serbian 
crimes in Bosnia. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-13265 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drnes075_s_94007" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-NES-94-075 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  18 Apr 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> Iran </F>
<H3> <TI>   Ukrainian Foreign Minister Zlenko Concludes Visit </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Ukrainian Foreign Minister Zlenko Concludes Visit </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Discusses Bosnia, Other Topics </H4>

<F P=102> LD1804182094 Tehran IRNA in English 1714 GMT 18 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1804182094 </F>
<F P=104>  Tehran IRNA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tehran, April 18, IRNA -- Ukrainian foreign 
minister, Anatoliy Zlenko, and Iran's vice-speaker of the 
Majles, Hassan Ruhani, here Monday discussed issues of mutual 
interests and international and regional developments including 
the crisis in Bosnia-Herzegovina. 
  Zlenko described Tehran-Kiev ties as "good" and called for 
further strengthening of mutual relations in cultural, economic 
and diplomatic fields. 
  Zlenko who arrived here Sunday on a three-day official visit 
also briefed Ruhani on the recent parliamentary election in 
Ukraine. 
  Ruhani for his part expressed pleasure over the developments 
in the former Soviet Union and over the independence of its 
republics. 
  On the plight and genocide of Muslims in Bosnia-Herzegovina 
Ruhani critisized international organizations for their 
indifference and called for regional cooperation to put an end 
to the crimes being committed by the Serbs. 
  He described the situation in Bosnia-Herzegovina as the 
"century's greatest disaster". 
  Commenting on Iran's mediation efforts in Tajikistan and the 
Caucasus, Ruhani called for international and regional 
cooperation to defuse the tensions. 
  The vice-speaker of the Majles also underlined promotion of 
Kiev-Tehran parliamentary ties. 

</TEXT>

